  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most countries around the world, including China. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by moving it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear as though it comes from a legitimate source. This practice is illegal because it facilitates criminal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, and terrorism financing.\n\nIn China, money laundering is strictly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China** and related regulations. Financial institutions and other entities are required to implement robust anti-money laundering (AML) measures, such as conducting due diligence on customers, monitoring transactions, and reporting suspicious activities to the authorities. Violations of these laws can result in severe penalties, including fines, imprisonment, and other legal consequences. China actively participates in international efforts to combat money laundering, cooperation through organizations such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, demonstrating its commitment to maintaining the integrity of its financial system.",
